I now have everything I need. The root cause is clear and precise. Here is the full diagnosis, root cause, fix, and principle.

---

## Diagnosis

The portaled active label appears **to the right of the rail** and clips past the viewport edge. The in-rail hover labels (`.label`) sit to the left, positioned with:

```scss
// .label — in-rail, positioned relative to .notch
right: calc(100% + #{$portfolio-spacing-03});
```

`right: calc(100% + gap)` means **"place my right edge `gap` pixels left of the notch's left edge."** That rightward reference point is the **notch's left edge** (`notch.getBoundingClientRect().left`).

The portaled anchor uses the exact mirror of that formula as its CSS transform:

```scss
// .highlightLabelAnchor — portaled, position: fixed
transform: translate(calc(-100% - #{$portfolio-spacing-03}), -50%);
```

`translate(-100% - gap, -50%)` means **"shift my right edge `gap` pixels left of wherever `left` is set."** So for the two to align, `left` must be set to `notch.left` — the **notch's left edge** — which is exactly what the `compute()` function now does (`r.left`).

So why is it still broken? The JS was changed, but **the transform in the CSS is wrong**. The current SCSS reads:

```scss
transform: translate(calc(-100% - #{$portfolio-spacing-03}), -50%);
```

`translate(X, Y)` interprets the **X value as a percentage of the element's own width**, but the `calc()` here mixes `-100%` (element-width-relative) and `- $portfolio-spacing-03` (absolute px). That subtraction is **correct in intent**, but it is evaluated as:

> `left` = `notch.left` → shift left by `(elementWidth + spacer)` → right edge lands at `notch.left - spacer` ✓

…on paper. The real bug is one layer up: **`$portfolio-spacing-03` is being interpolated with `#{}` inside a `calc()` that already lives inside `translate()`**. In Dart Sass / CSS the `#{}` interpolation strips the unit and the resulting `calc()` collapses to `translate(calc(-100% - 8px), -50%)` — that part is fine.

The **actual culprit** is that `translate()` is **a shorthand for `translateX() translateY()`**, and percentage values in `translateX()` resolve against the element's **own width** (`highlightLabelAnchor`). But `highlightLabelAnchor` has **no explicit width** — it is `position: fixed` with no `width` set, so its width is `0` (it is just a zero-size anchor point). Therefore:

- `-100%` of `0px` = `0px`
- The full transform reduces to `translate(calc(0px - 8px), -50%)` = `translate(-8px, -50%)`
- The label's **left** edge is placed at `notch.left - 8px`, not its **right** edge — the label extends **rightward** from the notch, straight off the right viewport edge.

The fix the previous engineer attempted — re-anchoring `left` from the tick to the notch — **does not change this** because the zero-width wrapper means the percentage component was already zero in both cases.

**Root cause: `AP-072` — percentage-in-translate applied to a zero-intrinsic-width fixed-position wrapper.** The `width: 0` anchor idiom is valid, but only if the `translate` is replaced with `right`-based positioning so the browser can resolve the offset without needing an element width.

---

## Fix

The cleanest solution is to **stop relying on `translateX(-100%)` for the rightward offset entirely**, and instead:

1. Give `highlightLabelAnchor` `right: 0; width: 0` positioning semantics by setting the `left` coordinate to `notch.left` **and** letting CSS push the label leftward via `right: $portfolio-spacing-03` on the inner span — exactly how `.label` works inside `.notch`.
2. Or, equivalently and with zero JS change: keep `left: notch.left` but replace the broken `translate(-100% - spacer)` with `translateX(-100%)` on the **inner `highlightLabel` span** (which has real, measurable content width) and absorb the spacer as a negative `margin-right` or `right` offset on that span.

**Option B is the minimal, correct fix** — move the percentage-based translate to the element that has width, and express the spacer separately.

### `src/components/ScrollSpy.module.scss`

```scss
// BEFORE (broken — -100% resolves against the zero-width anchor)
.highlightLabelAnchor {
  position: fixed;
  transform: translate(calc(-100% - #{$portfolio-spacing-03}), -50%);
  color: #fff;
  mix-blend-mode: difference;
  z-index: 41;
  pointer-events: none;
  will-change: top, left;
}

.highlightLabel {
  display: inline-block;
  font-family: $portfolio-font-mono;
  font-size: $portfolio-type-xs;
  line-height: 1;
  font-weight: 500;
  white-space: nowrap;
  will-change: transform, opacity;

  &[data-depth="1"] {
    font-weight: 400;
  }
}
```

```scss
// AFTER — anchor is a true zero-size pin; span owns the width-relative shift
.highlightLabelAnchor {
  position: fixed;
  // Vertically centre on the notch midpoint.
  // No X transform here — this element has no width; -100% would be 0px.
  transform: translateY(-50%);
  color: #fff;
  mix-blend-mode: difference;
  z-index: 41;
  pointer-events: none;
  will-change: top, left;
}

.highlightLabel {
  display: inline-block;
  font-family: $portfolio-font-mono;
  font-size: $portfolio-type-xs;
  line-height: 1;
  font-weight: 500;
  white-space: nowrap;
  // translateX(-100%) now resolves against the span's own content width
  // (the text). The additional -$portfolio-spacing-03 matches the spacer
  // used by the in-rail .label rule so both stacks share the same gutter.
  transform: translateX(calc(-100% - #{$portfolio-spacing-03}));
  will-change: transform, opacity;

  &[data-depth="1"] {
    font-weight: 400;
  }
}
```

### `src/components/ScrollSpy.tsx` — no JS changes required

The `compute()` function is already correct (`r.left` on the notch). No changes needed.

However, since `highlightLabel` now carries a **base CSS `transform`** and Framer Motion will **write its own `transform` inline** (clobbering it), we must fold the base offset into the Framer Motion `animate` values so Motion owns the full transform:

```tsx
// BEFORE — Motion only animates x/opacity; base transform lives in CSS
<motion.span
  className={styles.highlightLabel}
  data-depth={highlightDepth || undefined}
  initial={false}
  animate={{
    opacity: highlightVisible && overlayPos ? 1 : 0,
    x: highlightVisible && overlayPos ? 0 : 4,
  }}
  transition={{
    duration: isDragging ? 0 : DURATION.fast,
    ease: EASING.standard,
  }}
>
```

```tsx
// AFTER — Motion drives x from the full-offset base so it never clobbers
// the repositioning transform. CSS `transform` on .highlightLabel is removed;
// the gutter offset lives here as the resting `x` value.
//
// LABEL_OFFSET_PX must match $portfolio-spacing-03 (8 px).
// The -100% of element width cannot be expressed as a plain px constant here,
// so we keep the base translate on the anchor (Y only) and let Motion's `x`
// carry only the small gutter nudge. The key change: remove translateX from
// the CSS and instead wire the enter/exit x animation relative to 0.
// Motion then never fights a pre-existing CSS transform.

const GUTTER_PX = 8; // mirrors $portfolio-spacing-03

// In the JSX:
<motion.span
  className={styles.highlightLabel}
  data-depth={highlightDepth || undefined}
  initial={false}
  animate={{
    opacity: highlightVisible && overlayPos ? 1 : 0,
    x: highlightVisible && overlayPos ? 0 : 4,
  }}
  transition={{
    duration: isDragging ? 0 : DURATION.fast,
    ease: EASING.standard,
  }}
>
```

Wait — removing `translateX` from CSS and keeping `x` in Motion is actually fine *as long as* we absorb the full horizontal offset another way. The cleanest split, avoiding any fighting between CSS and Motion transforms, is:

**Put only `translateY(-50%)` on the anchor (no X), and on the span use `right: 0` + absolute positioning so the span's right edge pins to `notch.left`:**

### Final, conflict-free `ScrollSpy.module.scss` changes

```scss
.highlightLabelAnchor {
  position: fixed;
  // Only vertical centering. Zero width → no percentage X possible here.
  transform: translateY(-50%);
  color: #fff;
  mix-blend-mode: difference;
  z-index: 41;
  pointer-events: none;
  will-change: top, left;
  // Establish a containing block for the absolutely-positioned child.
  // Width/height 0 — purely a coordinate pin.
}

.highlightLabel {
  position: absolute;
  // Right edge of the label = left edge of anchor (= notch's left edge)
  // minus the gutter spacer. Mirrors .label { right: calc(100% + spacer) }
  // exactly. Because this is absolute inside a 0×0 anchor, 100% = 0, so
  // we use `right` with an explicit spacer instead of translate.
  right: $portfolio-spacing-03;
  top: 50%;
  transform: translateY(-50%); // vertical centering only — has real height
  display: inline-block;
  font-family: $portfolio-font-mono;
  font-size: $portfolio-type-xs;
  line-height: 1;
  font-weight: 500;
  white-space: nowrap;
  will-change: transform, opacity;

  &[data-depth="1"] {
    font-weight: 400;
  }
}
```

And update the Framer Motion `animate` in `ScrollSpy.tsx` to match — Motion's `x` is now relative to the `right`-positioned base, so the enter/exit slide of `4 px` still works correctly:

```tsx
// ScrollSpy.tsx — no structural changes, just confirm the animate block
// is unchanged. Motion's x nudge is a small delta on top of the CSS `right`
// position; they do not fight because `right` is not a transform property.
<motion.span
  className={styles.highlightLabel}
  data-depth={highlightDepth || undefined}
  initial={false}
  animate={{
    opacity: highlightVisible && overlayPos ? 1 : 0,
    x: highlightVisible && overlayPos ? 0 : 4,   // ← unchanged, still valid
  }}
  transition={{
    duration: isDragging ? 0 : DURATION.fast,
    ease: EASING.standard,
  }}
>
  {highlightSection.label}
</motion.span>
```

This is the complete change set. No JS coordinate math changes. No new tokens.

---

## Principle

**AP-072 — Never use percentage `translateX` on a zero-intrinsic-width element.**

`translate(X%, …)` resolves `X%` against `offsetWidth`. A `position: fixed` element with no explicit `width`, no children with layout (or children that are `position: absolute`/`fixed` themselves), and no padding has `offsetWidth = 0`. The percentage collapses silently to `0px`; no browser warning is emitted. The pattern is invisible in isolation and breaks only when the anchor carries its own offset responsibility.

**The invariant:** if an element is used as a zero-size coordinate pin, all horizontal placement must come from `left`/`right` on itself or its children — never from `translateX(N%)` on the pin itself. Reserve `translateX(-100%)` for elements with real content width, or use `right` positioning to let the browser resolve the offset against the known coordinate rather than the unknown width.
